WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en-US

00:00:00.160 --> 00:00:05.360
This is Part 1 of a 2-part Blender tutorial&nbsp;
covering the very basics of setting up materials&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:05.360 --> 00:00:09.840
and shading in Blender. I’ll give a thorough&nbsp;
overview of how to add materials, how basic&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:09.840 --> 00:00:14.720
material nodes work, and we’ll cover some of&nbsp;
the more common nodes you’ll use. In part 2,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:14.720 --> 00:00:18.800
we will get in to PBR texture materials&nbsp;
which are super realistic materials.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:18.800 --> 00:00:22.720
I’ll save some quick but valuable tips&nbsp;
for the end. If nodes are confusing,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:22.720 --> 00:00:26.560
I promise this should demystify&nbsp;
a lot of it for you. Let’s go.&nbsp;

00:00:26.560 --> 00:00:31.360
A quick note, I will be doing everything&nbsp;
in Cycles. These materials will work&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:31.360 --> 00:00:35.680
in Eevee too but sometimes the settings are a&nbsp;
little bit off between the two render engines.

00:00:36.560 --> 00:00:41.760
We start with materials at the material properties&nbsp;
panel. With an object selected, this panel&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:41.760 --> 00:00:46.800
displays materials assigned to the object.&nbsp;
This is a default material that’s assigned.&nbsp;

00:00:46.800 --> 00:00:51.200
Objects can have more than one material&nbsp;
assigned to them in these material slots.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:51.200 --> 00:00:55.760
Pressing the plus icon adds a new material&nbsp;
slot but there’s no material in the second&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:55.760 --> 00:01:00.000
slot yet. We can either use this&nbsp;
drop down box to choose a material&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:04.240
already in our Blender scene or we can press&nbsp;
“New” to create a new one. Let’s do that.&nbsp;

00:01:04.880 --> 00:01:10.640
With the new material selected, a few tabs get&nbsp;
added below. We have preview, surface, volume,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:10.640 --> 00:01:15.040
displacement, settings and a few more.
By default, there will be nothing in the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:15.040 --> 00:01:19.200
displacement, nothing in the volume, but under&nbsp;
surface we have a whole bunch of settings.&nbsp;

00:01:19.840 --> 00:01:23.760
And preview is just the preview of the&nbsp;
material. You can choose different shapes&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:23.760 --> 00:01:27.520
to have the material previewed on.
But these three - the surface,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:27.520 --> 00:01:31.040
volume and displacement are the&nbsp;
three channels a material can have.&nbsp;

00:01:31.600 --> 00:01:36.320
Surface is everything on the outside surface&nbsp;
of the object. Like paint, wood, metal,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:36.320 --> 00:01:41.680
etc. It’s what you’re going to use the most.
Volume is how you want the three dimensional&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:41.680 --> 00:01:46.960
space inside the object to be filled. You’d&nbsp;
use this if you wanted to make smoke or fog&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:46.960 --> 00:01:50.880
inside of an object. You’d also use it&nbsp;
for liquids, clouds, things like that.&nbsp;

00:01:51.600 --> 00:01:55.360
Displacement is physical movement,&nbsp;
or displacement, of the mesh.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:55.360 --> 00:02:00.240
An example of when you’d use this is if you had a&nbsp;
brick wall and you wanted it so detailed that the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:00.240 --> 00:02:05.120
mesh actually popped outwards on the bricks&nbsp;
and sunk in where the mortar was. There are&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:05.120 --> 00:02:09.920
other ways to fake this look and we’ll get into&nbsp;
that in part 2, but that’s what displacement is.&nbsp;

00:02:10.640 --> 00:02:15.200
Let’s look at surface for now. Everything on&nbsp;
this panel is basically a summary of what’s&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:15.200 --> 00:02:20.560
actually been created using nodes in the shader&nbsp;
editor. For simple materials, you can handle all&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:20.560 --> 00:02:24.960
the settings right here, but once they get more&nbsp;
complex you’ll want to jump over to the nodes.&nbsp;

00:02:25.600 --> 00:02:31.680
At the top, it says surface and then it says&nbsp;
“Principled BSDF.” The principled BSDF is the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:31.680 --> 00:02:37.040
default shader for materials in Blender. It is&nbsp;
a very versatile shader that can create many of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:37.040 --> 00:02:42.480
the things you’ll want to make. What is a shader&nbsp;
by the way? A shader is a calculation of how to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:42.480 --> 00:02:47.200
output materials and how those materials&nbsp;
will interact with light in your scene.&nbsp;

00:02:47.200 --> 00:02:51.360
If we click the name of the shader, we can&nbsp;
choose from a long list of other shaders.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:51.360 --> 00:02:55.760
We aren’t going to cover them all and you won’t&nbsp;
use very many of them. This shader doesn’t have&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:55.760 --> 00:03:00.720
many options, but the Principled BSDF has a lot&nbsp;
more settings because it can do a lot more stuff.&nbsp;

00:03:01.280 --> 00:03:05.920
Remember how we added the second material. Well,&nbsp;
the first material is the material currently&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:05.920 --> 00:03:11.440
assigned to the plane by default. When a material&nbsp;
is placed in the first slot, it gets assigned to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:11.440 --> 00:03:16.640
the entire object. To change materials, we can go&nbsp;
into edit mode, select the portion of the mesh we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:16.640 --> 00:03:22.800
want to assign the second material to. Select the&nbsp;
material and then press “assign.” We could select&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:22.800 --> 00:03:26.800
different parts of the mesh and assign different&nbsp;
materials to different parts in this way.&nbsp;

00:03:28.400 --> 00:03:31.840
We can select the material slot&nbsp;
and press minus to remove the slot.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:32.400 --> 00:03:38.240
The removed material will still be available&nbsp;
to add to objects later until we close Blender.&nbsp;

00:03:38.240 --> 00:03:40.480
We can double click on the material in the slot,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:40.480 --> 00:03:46.160
or down here and rename it. I’ll rename it to&nbsp;
“Subscribe” just as a little reminder for you&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:46.160 --> 00:03:50.240
to subscribe and turn on notifications&nbsp;
so you don’t miss future tutorials.&nbsp;

00:03:50.240 --> 00:03:54.720
This is as far as we are going right here.&nbsp;
We are now heading over to the Shader Editor.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:54.720 --> 00:03:58.160
The best way to get there is to change&nbsp;
to the shading workspace at the top.

00:03:58.800 --> 00:04:03.040
Before we go any farther, there is an addon in&nbsp;
Blender called “Node Wrangler” that you want&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:03.040 --> 00:04:08.000
to have turned on pretty much all the&nbsp;
time. Go to edit, preferences, add ons&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:08.000 --> 00:04:12.160
and search for node wrangler. Check&nbsp;
the box next to it to activate it.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:12.160 --> 00:04:16.400
This addon enables a lot of things you can&nbsp;
do with the nodes. It should really just be&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:16.400 --> 00:04:19.840
incorporated into Blender by default&nbsp;
but for technical reasons it’s not.

00:04:21.120 --> 00:04:24.160
If your workspace isn’t&nbsp;
exactly like mine, don’t worry.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:24.160 --> 00:04:28.640
The important things are you should have&nbsp;
a 3D viewport set to material preview mode&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:28.640 --> 00:04:32.560
and you should have this big area known&nbsp;
as the shader editor. The properties&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:32.560 --> 00:04:36.560
panel should be over here on the side.
Let’s just cover a few basic things about&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:36.560 --> 00:04:41.280
the shader editor. In the top left, we&nbsp;
see a drop down box that says “object.”&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:41.280 --> 00:04:45.920
This means the shader editor is set to work&nbsp;
on object materials, which is what we want.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:45.920 --> 00:04:51.120
But we can change this to work on shading of the&nbsp;
world - which is the background of the scene, the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:51.120 --> 00:04:57.200
sky etc. This is how you could add an HDR image&nbsp;
to light your scene or to serve as a background.&nbsp;

00:04:57.920 --> 00:05:01.520
Up here we have some of the same&nbsp;
controls from the materials panel.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:01.520 --> 00:05:06.960
It shows our material slots and the materials&nbsp;
assigned to them. Now let’s talk about nodes.

00:05:07.760 --> 00:05:14.000
We have the principled BSDF node assigned to this&nbsp;
material. This large node is the principled bsdf&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:14.000 --> 00:05:16.960
with all the same options we&nbsp;
saw in the materials panel.&nbsp;

00:05:16.960 --> 00:05:22.160
But, you will always have this material output&nbsp;
node as well. You can select a node and press&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:22.160 --> 00:05:27.200
“G” to move it around or just click and drag it.&nbsp;
Many of the same shortcuts of Blender work in the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:27.200 --> 00:05:33.680
shader editor. If I have a node selected, Shift+D&nbsp;
duplicates it. Shift+A is how we add a new node.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:34.720 --> 00:05:38.240
And X deletes a node.
The material output node&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:38.240 --> 00:05:43.440
is the final output of whatever information&nbsp;
your nodes create. It has three channels. I&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:43.440 --> 00:05:48.320
mentioned these earlier. The Principled BSDF&nbsp;
is a surface shader so it’s plugged into the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:48.320 --> 00:05:54.240
surface input of this final output node.
All information in node editors flows from&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:54.240 --> 00:05:59.680
theleft to the right. So you put information into&nbsp;
the nodes on the left side, the nodes do something&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:59.680 --> 00:06:04.960
with that information and put out new information&nbsp;
on the right. Because the material output node is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:04.960 --> 00:06:11.040
the final output where all the nodes end, it only&nbsp;
has inputs on the left side. These dots for inputs&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:11.040 --> 00:06:16.320
and outputs are called sockets. The principled&nbsp;
BSDF node has a whole bunch of input sockets on&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:16.320 --> 00:06:21.680
the left but only one output socket on the right.
You’ll notice the sockets are different colors.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:21.680 --> 00:06:26.960
A green socket represents complete shader&nbsp;
information. If a node has a green output on it,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:26.960 --> 00:06:31.760
it is considered a “shader” meaning it can&nbsp;
be an end product that can be plugged into&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:31.760 --> 00:06:36.320
the final output node. You’ll often hear&nbsp;
“node” and “shader” used interchangeably,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:36.320 --> 00:06:40.640
but technically only some nodes - the nodes&nbsp;
with green outputs - are actually shaders.&nbsp;

00:06:41.280 --> 00:06:46.000
Yellow sockets indicate color information.&nbsp;
So, this base color for example,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:46.000 --> 00:06:50.880
we could plug any sort of color information&nbsp;
into this and the socket will recognize it&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:50.880 --> 00:06:56.560
as color. This could be a color image.
The grey sockets are value inputs. These&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:56.560 --> 00:07:02.720
could be numerical values of any kind, but often&nbsp;
range between zero and one. Many of these settings&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:02.720 --> 00:07:08.400
on the BSDF have values that range from zero to&nbsp;
one. Zero means there’s none of the effect and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:08.400 --> 00:07:13.520
one means the effect is turned all the way up.
Let’s look at roughness as an example. Roughness&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:13.520 --> 00:07:17.520
is how rough a material’s surface is&nbsp;
and it affects the reflection of light.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:17.520 --> 00:07:22.880
Zero would be a completely smooth surface which&nbsp;
is unrealistic for most materials. One would be&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:22.880 --> 00:07:28.240
very rough. You can actually click this value and&nbsp;
type in a value higher than one if you want to.&nbsp;

00:07:28.240 --> 00:07:33.040
These grey sockets can also accept black&nbsp;
and white or grey scale values. Why are&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:33.040 --> 00:07:38.080
black and white or grey scale images important?
Well it’s unlikely that you’ll want a material to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:38.080 --> 00:07:43.280
be exactly the same roughness everywhere.&nbsp;
So, these zero to one values allow us to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:43.280 --> 00:07:48.560
map values to different areas of the material&nbsp;
using black and white or gray scale coloring.&nbsp;

00:07:48.560 --> 00:07:53.200
Here’s an example of a roughness map that can&nbsp;
be plugged into this socket. Zero is represented&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:53.200 --> 00:07:57.680
by black. One is represented by white and&nbsp;
everything in between is represented by a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:57.680 --> 00:08:03.120
shade of grey. The darker the gray, the closer&nbsp;
it is to zero so the lower the effect will be&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:03.120 --> 00:08:07.840
in that part of the material. And the lighter&nbsp;
it is, the closer it is to one so the effect&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:07.840 --> 00:08:12.960
will be stronger there. This image plugged into&nbsp;
this roughness socket would use grey scale data&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:12.960 --> 00:08:17.760
to map out roughness values over the object.
So, that’s what the grey sockets are - they’re&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:17.760 --> 00:08:21.520
value inputs that can also be&nbsp;
mapped with grey scale images.&nbsp;

00:08:21.520 --> 00:08:27.040
This concept will be important in both procedural&nbsp;
and PBR texturing that we cover in part two.&nbsp;

00:08:27.040 --> 00:08:32.400
The last color here is purple. Purple sockets deal&nbsp;
with vector information which is information that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:32.400 --> 00:08:37.360
either tells Blender where to map something or&nbsp;
where to move something. It’s hard to explain,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:37.360 --> 00:08:42.320
but you’ll see this mostly with normal maps&nbsp;
and material mapping which we will cover soon.&nbsp;

00:08:42.320 --> 00:08:48.080
For the most part, you usually plug outputs&nbsp;
into like-colored input sockets. So, green&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:48.080 --> 00:08:54.000
always needs to go to green, purple into&nbsp;
purple, etc. This is not 100% always the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:54.000 --> 00:08:58.000
case with yellows and greys. Sometimes you&nbsp;
have a black and white output that you’re&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:58.000 --> 00:09:03.680
going to use in a color socket and vice versa.&nbsp;
But, yellows are looking for color information&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:03.680 --> 00:09:08.400
and greys won’t recognize color information&nbsp;
other than black, white and grey scale.

00:09:09.520 --> 00:09:14.160
So the Principled BSDF shader in Blender has a&nbsp;
lot of settings. Probably more than any other&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:14.160 --> 00:09:18.720
because it does a lot of things. This was only&nbsp;
added to Blender a few years ago and before,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:18.720 --> 00:09:23.840
you actually had to combine a lot of nodes to&nbsp;
be able to do what this node can do by itself.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:23.840 --> 00:09:27.360
It’s important enough to go over a&nbsp;
lot of these settings. I’ll be honest,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:27.360 --> 00:09:31.120
some of them I’ve never used and am not&nbsp;
going to be able to adequately explain.&nbsp;

00:09:31.120 --> 00:09:36.160
But, base color is pretty self-explanatory. It’s&nbsp;
the starting color of the material without any&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:36.160 --> 00:09:39.040
effects like reflectiveness&nbsp;
or roughness added to it.&nbsp;

00:09:39.040 --> 00:09:43.520
The next three are for subsurface scattering&nbsp;
which is what happens to light that penetrates&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:43.520 --> 00:09:48.160
the surface and scatters underneath it. The&nbsp;
best example of this is human skin. When light&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:48.160 --> 00:09:53.760
hits skin, some of it goes through and scatters&nbsp;
underneath giving it a pinkish hue. The subsurface&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:53.760 --> 00:09:58.880
scattering settings can replicate that effect.
Metallic. I’ll try to explain this as best I&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:58.880 --> 00:10:04.240
can. Materials that are truly metal have a&nbsp;
reflective property but also have their own color,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:04.240 --> 00:10:09.360
so it’s different than say a glass mirror.&nbsp;
There are two basic workflows for shading that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:09.360 --> 00:10:14.960
you’ll see and they are a metalness workflow and a&nbsp;
specular workflow. Some artists choose to use the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:14.960 --> 00:10:20.320
metallic input and some the specular, depending&nbsp;
on the material and their personal preferences.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:20.320 --> 00:10:25.200
These are different from each other but are both&nbsp;
ways of giving a material reflective properties.&nbsp;

00:10:25.920 --> 00:10:30.720
Roughness we kind of covered, but it’s&nbsp;
how rough the surface is on a very tiny,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:30.720 --> 00:10:35.840
nearly microscopic level and affects the&nbsp;
reflection. Paper has a high roughness value.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:35.840 --> 00:10:41.280
On a microscopic level, it is not smooth and that&nbsp;
roughness will make it not reflect light as well.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:41.280 --> 00:10:45.840
Most glass will have a very low roughness and&nbsp;
even at the microscopic level is very smooth.&nbsp;

00:10:46.720 --> 00:10:51.200
Anistropic, sheen and clearcoat are some&nbsp;
advanced characteristics you can give&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:51.200 --> 00:10:55.040
a material that we aren’t going to cover&nbsp;
right now. Transmission is how much light&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:55.040 --> 00:10:58.960
is allowed to pass through the material&nbsp;
rather than be reflected off of it.&nbsp;

00:10:58.960 --> 00:11:03.680
Emission is light that the material actually&nbsp;
emits from itself. You can give the emitted&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:03.680 --> 00:11:09.280
light its own color and strength. You can actually&nbsp;
use this to have objects light your scene or for a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:09.280 --> 00:11:14.000
variety of effects. If you’re emitting light&nbsp;
from a material it’s usually going to drown&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:14.000 --> 00:11:18.080
out any other settings you have up&nbsp;
here so this is usually used by itself.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:18.080 --> 00:11:22.400
There’s also an emission shader that only&nbsp;
does emission if you want to use that instead.&nbsp;

00:11:23.040 --> 00:11:28.160
Alpha is transparency. Wherever you see the&nbsp;
word alpha in pretty much any graphics software,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:28.160 --> 00:11:33.840
it’s referring to the transparent quality. One&nbsp;
is no transparency (a little backwards it seems)&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:33.840 --> 00:11:38.560
and zero is full transparency. That’s&nbsp;
just how alpha values work. Of course,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:38.560 --> 00:11:43.120
this and all these other settings can be mapped&nbsp;
to an object so you could have parts of your&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:43.120 --> 00:11:48.240
material transparent and parts not transparent.&nbsp;
You would use a grey scale map for to do this.&nbsp;

00:11:50.720 --> 00:11:56.240
The normal input is for a normal map. Normal&nbsp;
maps are a way to fake depth and shadows in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:56.240 --> 00:12:01.120
your material without actually changing the&nbsp;
geometry of the mesh. They are very useful.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:01.120 --> 00:12:05.760
Here’s an image of a surface with no normal&nbsp;
map. And here’s an image with the normal&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:05.760 --> 00:12:11.360
map. No difference in the actual mesh, just using&nbsp;
normal data to fake the look of depth and height.&nbsp;

00:12:12.400 --> 00:12:16.640
Alright, so let’s look at some other node&nbsp;
options in the Blender shader editor.

00:12:17.440 --> 00:12:21.920
To add a node in the shader editor, you&nbsp;
press Shift+A and you get this menu. The&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:21.920 --> 00:12:25.840
nodes are all categorized into groups and&nbsp;
there are quite a few of them. Often you’ll&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:25.840 --> 00:12:29.840
know what node you’re looking for and can&nbsp;
search for it by name in the search field.&nbsp;

00:12:30.400 --> 00:12:35.360
You’ll see a category called “shader.” Remember&nbsp;
a shader is a node with a finished output ready&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:35.360 --> 00:12:39.440
to be plugged into the output node.
Some of them are for surfaces,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:39.440 --> 00:12:44.320
some are for volume. You can also go over here&nbsp;
in the shader properties and see the options for&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:44.320 --> 00:12:49.520
different shaders. Most of them are very simple,&nbsp;
don’t have a lot of inputs or are designed to do&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:49.520 --> 00:12:54.480
one very specific thing. Like the glass&nbsp;
shader. The Principled BSDF is so useful&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:54.480 --> 00:12:59.440
that it’s almost always what you start with.
The mix shader can be added to combine two&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:59.440 --> 00:13:04.560
shaders together. I will duplicate this&nbsp;
shader and show you how to mix two shaders.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:04.560 --> 00:13:08.400
I’ll give one a red base color and one&nbsp;
a blue base color for demonstration.&nbsp;

00:13:09.040 --> 00:13:15.360
To connect sockets, you can drag the output socket&nbsp;
of one node over to the input socket of another&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:15.360 --> 00:13:19.840
and when it’s connected, this line will appear&nbsp;
to show the path of the information. There are&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:19.840 --> 00:13:24.960
a few ways to disconnect a shader and one of&nbsp;
them is to just click the output connection,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:24.960 --> 00:13:29.840
drag it off and let go. I’ve got a faster way&nbsp;
as one of my tips at the end of the video.&nbsp;

00:13:29.840 --> 00:13:33.040
By the way, I would love to get a like&nbsp;
on this video if you’ve made it this far,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:33.040 --> 00:13:36.800
it really helps and is really, really&nbsp;
appreciated. Thank you so much!&nbsp;

00:13:36.800 --> 00:13:40.880
If you drag and drop a node onto a&nbsp;
connection, Blender will insert it for you&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:40.880 --> 00:13:45.840
between the two nodes - if it can, meaning if&nbsp;
there are appropriate sockets to plug into.&nbsp;

00:13:45.840 --> 00:13:49.440
So back to the mix shader. It has&nbsp;
two green inputs for you to connect&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:49.440 --> 00:13:53.600
two shaders you want to combine. The&nbsp;
factor, which you will see a lot,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:53.600 --> 00:13:58.320
is how you want the shaders combined. With this&nbsp;
setup, turning it all the way to zero will be&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:58.320 --> 00:14:03.680
100% the top shader. Turning it all the&nbsp;
way to one will be 100% the bottom shader.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:03.680 --> 00:14:08.000
Putting it somewhere in the middle will&nbsp;
be a faded combination of both shaders.&nbsp;

00:14:08.000 --> 00:14:13.520
But, you notice the factor shader has a grey&nbsp;
input node. This means we can map this factor.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:13.520 --> 00:14:19.040
If we plugged in a grey scale map or a node&nbsp;
that maps values from zero to one, we would&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:19.040 --> 00:14:24.240
tell Blender to put the top shader where there is&nbsp;
black and the bottom shader where there is white&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:24.240 --> 00:14:29.040
and to mix the two together where there is grey.
I’m going to leave these two shaders connected.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:29.040 --> 00:14:31.920
And we are going to look at a few other&nbsp;
important nodes that come into play.

00:14:32.640 --> 00:14:38.560
We’ll press shift+a and in the search bar, type&nbsp;
in “color” and choose the color ramp node. You&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:38.560 --> 00:14:44.480
will use this node a lot. It’s a gradient node.&nbsp;
It defaults with two gradient points, a black on&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:44.480 --> 00:14:49.520
the far left and a white on the far right with a&nbsp;
completely smooth and linear transition between.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:49.520 --> 00:14:53.600
There are different settings to choose for how&nbsp;
the gradient is interpolated - that means how it&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:53.600 --> 00:14:59.040
transitions or fades from one point to another.
It also has a factor input on the left and on&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:59.040 --> 00:15:04.080
the right, it has both a color output and&nbsp;
an alpha output. The color ramp can generate&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:04.080 --> 00:15:09.360
color information. You can select one of these&nbsp;
points and choose a color. This can be used for&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:09.360 --> 00:15:14.880
all sorts of gradients in your materials. You can&nbsp;
click the plus icon to add a control point. This&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:14.880 --> 00:15:18.880
could allow you to add a new color to the&nbsp;
gradient or just use it for more control.&nbsp;

00:15:19.440 --> 00:15:24.400
The color ramp is often used as a factor input&nbsp;
and this is one of those times where you will&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:24.400 --> 00:15:28.960
actually plug a yellow color output&nbsp;
into a grey input socket. IF.. your&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:28.960 --> 00:15:32.880
colors are all going to be grey scale.
We will see the color ramp again soon.

00:15:34.080 --> 00:15:37.680
One category of material nodes&nbsp;
in Blender is texture nodes.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:37.680 --> 00:15:42.720
Shift+A to add a node and find the category&nbsp;
labeled texture. These are a bunch of different&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:42.720 --> 00:15:47.760
ways to procedurally create black and white or&nbsp;
grey scale textures that can later be combined&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:47.760 --> 00:15:52.880
and tweaked to get procedural looks that you want.
We’ll look at the musgrave texture first, which is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:52.880 --> 00:15:58.480
commonly used to add procedural grunge effects.&nbsp;
I’ll plug the height output into the color input&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:58.480 --> 00:16:03.360
of the Principled BSDF just to show you what it&nbsp;
looks like. Since Musgrave is outputting black&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:03.360 --> 00:16:07.840
and white color, it’s ok to plug it into the&nbsp;
color input socket so long as we understand we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:07.840 --> 00:16:12.240
are only getting black and white out of it.
This is the basic musgrave texture pattern.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:12.240 --> 00:16:16.880
There are different types of musgrave you can&nbsp;
choose from here. Where it says 3D, you can&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:16.880 --> 00:16:22.080
choose other dimensions, I almost always leave&nbsp;
it at 3D although 2D would work since the plane&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:22.800 --> 00:16:29.440
is a 2D object. Choosing 4D adds a W value down&nbsp;
here and whenever you see the W value in shading,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:29.440 --> 00:16:34.320
it’s an animation factor. It can make&nbsp;
the texture move over time. Change the W&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:34.320 --> 00:16:40.560
and the texture moves. You can keyframe this value&nbsp;
to have the texture be animated which is awesome.&nbsp;

00:16:40.560 --> 00:16:43.600
The other settings also adjust&nbsp;
the look of the musgrave. Scale&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:43.600 --> 00:16:48.480
and detail are probably the most helpful.
A very, very common use of the color ramp&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:48.480 --> 00:16:54.240
that we looked at before is to add it after a&nbsp;
texture node, so let’s do that. Shift+A and we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:54.240 --> 00:16:59.520
find the color ramp under converter. For nodes you&nbsp;
use repeatedly, I’ve got some tips to add them to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:59.520 --> 00:17:04.240
the editor faster at the end of this video.
So let’s drop the color ramp in between the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:04.240 --> 00:17:09.360
musgrave texture and the principled shader.&nbsp;
Notice this now has a grey socket into a grey&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:09.360 --> 00:17:14.560
socket on the left and yellow into a yellow on&nbsp;
the right. It’s almost like it was meant to be.&nbsp;

00:17:15.120 --> 00:17:20.320
The colorramp now acts as a gradient control for&nbsp;
the transitioning between black and white areas&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:20.320 --> 00:17:25.600
in the texture node. If we move the white closer&nbsp;
to the black, it shortens the transitional fade&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:25.600 --> 00:17:30.880
between black and white on the texture. Moving&nbsp;
the black up will remove some of the white.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:30.880 --> 00:17:35.840
Another trick is to select the white, then use&nbsp;
the color selector here. Darken the white and it&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:35.840 --> 00:17:40.080
subdues the texture pattern everywhere.
And lastly, since the color ramp does&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:40.080 --> 00:17:45.200
output RGB colors, we can change the colors to&nbsp;
actually output a colored texture if we want.&nbsp;

00:17:45.760 --> 00:17:48.480
I’ll quickly show you some other&nbsp;
texture nodes and we’ll move on.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:49.040 --> 00:17:55.440
Voronoi, voronoi, voronoi is a useful texture&nbsp;
that you can get a lot of cool looks out of.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:57.520 --> 00:18:00.240
The brick texture allows you&nbsp;
to make procedural bricks or&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:00.240 --> 00:18:07.600
blocky textures. Lots of settings on this one.
The wave texture allows you to add bands or rings.&nbsp;

00:18:07.600 --> 00:18:12.640
Here’s the really interesting part. These&nbsp;
textures can be used as inputs for other textures.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:12.640 --> 00:18:18.880
I could plug the voronoi into the wave scale&nbsp;
and get this. I could plug the musgrave into&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:18.880 --> 00:18:25.200
the scale and get this. Or plug the voronoi&nbsp;
into the musgrave and get something like this.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:25.760 --> 00:18:30.000
There are endless combinations of these you&nbsp;
can use to get different effects. And there&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:30.000 --> 00:18:34.400
are countless Blender tutorials out there that&nbsp;
show you different ways to play around with this.

00:18:35.440 --> 00:18:39.600
Another way to mix and combine texturing&nbsp;
effects or colors is using the Mix&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:39.600 --> 00:18:44.720
RGB node. The Mix RGB node in Blender acts&nbsp;
just like the Mix Shader we looked at earlier&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:44.720 --> 00:18:49.600
but instead of being for shader outputs, it’s&nbsp;
for color - including greyscale color values.&nbsp;

00:18:49.600 --> 00:18:55.280
I’ll add a Mix RGB node. I’ll plug a musgrave&nbsp;
texture into one yellow socket and a voronoi&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:55.280 --> 00:19:01.200
texture into another. Again, we have this factor&nbsp;
setting that controls how much of each one we get.&nbsp;

00:19:01.200 --> 00:19:05.200
For this one, we also have a lot of different&nbsp;
Blending modes. If you’ve used other graphics&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:05.200 --> 00:19:09.280
software like Photoshop or whatever, you’ve&nbsp;
probably seen these before. They are different&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:09.280 --> 00:19:13.440
formulas for how to blend colors together.&nbsp;
Not gonna go into a lot of detail in here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:13.440 --> 00:19:17.680
but the default mix might give you a&nbsp;
very different effect than “add” or&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:17.680 --> 00:19:22.080
“multiply” would and depending on what you’re&nbsp;
going for, you may use different blend modes.&nbsp;

00:19:22.080 --> 00:19:26.800
For demonstration, I’m going to add a wave&nbsp;
texture and plug it into the factor to control&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:26.800 --> 00:19:31.520
how these two textures are mixed together.&nbsp;
You see the bands from the wave texture have&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:31.520 --> 00:19:37.280
separated where the musgrave and voronoi show up.
Of course adding a color ramp in here can give us&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:37.280 --> 00:19:43.360
even more control. Or we could add color to&nbsp;
this. We’ve used one texture node as a map&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:43.360 --> 00:19:47.600
for how to combine two other texture&nbsp;
nodes. And this is a very simple setup.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:47.600 --> 00:19:51.360
There are endless combinations of how you&nbsp;
can mix and match textures to get all sorts&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:51.360 --> 00:19:55.200
of procedural effects. And again there are&nbsp;
tons of tutorials on different ways to do it.

00:19:56.000 --> 00:20:00.240
So now let’s talk about mapping textures&nbsp;
onto an object. With this simple texture,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:00.240 --> 00:20:04.720
it isn’t that big of a deal but it will be&nbsp;
with a more complicated and when we get into&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:04.720 --> 00:20:10.720
PBR texturing in part 2. To add a texture mapping&nbsp;
setup to this, we actually have to add two nodes.&nbsp;

00:20:10.720 --> 00:20:15.040
The first is a mapping node. This node’s&nbsp;
purple vector output will plug into the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:15.040 --> 00:20:19.840
purple vector input here. And we immediately&nbsp;
notice that the entire texture disappears.&nbsp;

00:20:20.400 --> 00:20:24.240
This node is a control node with all&nbsp;
the mapping controls. But it doesn’t&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:24.240 --> 00:20:28.560
even know where to start without the help of&nbsp;
another node, the texture coordinate node.&nbsp;

00:20:29.120 --> 00:20:33.040
The texture coordinate node has a bunch of&nbsp;
different ways that the texture can be told&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:33.040 --> 00:20:38.000
how to be mapped in Blender. Different uses may&nbsp;
require different outputs here. Generally for&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:38.000 --> 00:20:42.720
procedural things, Object is going to be your&nbsp;
best bet. But, you see this has adjusted the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:42.720 --> 00:20:47.760
material based on the size of the object. So, an&nbsp;
alternative could be the “generated” which is kind&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:47.760 --> 00:20:53.120
of just the default. When we get to PBR stuff,&nbsp;
where we will actually be using images that may&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:53.120 --> 00:20:57.920
need to be placed on very specific parts of the&nbsp;
mesh, as well as multiple images which need to be&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:57.920 --> 00:21:03.360
placed in the exact same way, we will use UV.
So this mapping node gives us all sorts of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:03.360 --> 00:21:08.480
control on where this texture is mapped on&nbsp;
the object. We can change the location along&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:08.480 --> 00:21:13.360
all three axes. This is only a 2 dimensional&nbsp;
object, so some of this isn’t as important.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:13.360 --> 00:21:18.640
We can rotate the material and we can scale&nbsp;
the material along each of the three axes.

00:21:19.280 --> 00:21:23.920
One main point on nodes we should mention&nbsp;
here is an output can go into many inputs,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:26.960 --> 00:21:30.400
but an input can only have&nbsp;
one connection going into it.&nbsp;

00:21:30.400 --> 00:21:34.640
Often, we’ll use the same mapping setup&nbsp;
and feed it into multiple different nodes.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:34.640 --> 00:21:38.080
But, if we try to feed two nodes into&nbsp;
one input, it’s not going to work.

00:21:38.960 --> 00:21:44.080
Another node you will see used a lot is the math&nbsp;
node. I hate math, but this node isn’t too bad.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:44.080 --> 00:21:49.200
It could be plugged in between two other nodes and&nbsp;
then it can run a simple math formula on the data&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:49.200 --> 00:21:53.760
before it gets to the second node. Remember&nbsp;
black and white values have values of zero&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:53.760 --> 00:21:58.880
and one respectively. Well, maybe you want&nbsp;
to amplify those values by multiplying them.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:58.880 --> 00:22:04.240
Or maybe you want to take two values and add them&nbsp;
together. The math node does this and a lot more.

00:22:05.120 --> 00:22:09.040
Sometimes in Blender, you want something&nbsp;
to be transparent or translucent.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:09.040 --> 00:22:12.880
There are both transparent and translucent&nbsp;
shaders in Blender that can be combined&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:12.880 --> 00:22:17.920
with other shaders or used by themselves.
More often, I find the glass shader useful.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:18.720 --> 00:22:25.040
On this, you’ll see an IOR setting. Whenever you&nbsp;
see IOR it means Index of Refraction, which is one&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:25.040 --> 00:22:29.840
of the terms I cover in my Blender Terminology&nbsp;
video that I recommend beginners check out.&nbsp;

00:22:29.840 --> 00:22:36.400
Different materials reflect light at different&nbsp;
angles. Your regular glass has an IOR of 1.45&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:36.400 --> 00:22:41.040
which is the default value for this node.&nbsp;
Other materials like plastic, water,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:41.040 --> 00:22:45.520
thicker or thinner glass will have different&nbsp;
IOR’s. So the glass shader can actually be&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:45.520 --> 00:22:49.680
used for more than just glass. The roughness&nbsp;
value can be adjusted and this is a good&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:49.680 --> 00:22:54.880
demonstration of what roughness does. Higher is&nbsp;
less reflective while lower is more reflective.

00:22:56.400 --> 00:23:00.720
Everything we’ve covered so far has dealt with&nbsp;
the surface channel of materials but volume is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:00.720 --> 00:23:04.640
something you might want to use as well. There&nbsp;
are only a handful of volume shaders and I’ll&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:04.640 --> 00:23:09.680
need a 3 dimensional object to demonstrate this.&nbsp;
So I’ll add a cube and give it a new material.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:09.680 --> 00:23:14.240
I’ll delete the principled shader because I don’t&nbsp;
want this object to have a surface, I just want it&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:14.240 --> 00:23:18.720
to have volume. The object turns black until&nbsp;
you plug something into the volume channel.&nbsp;

00:23:19.280 --> 00:23:24.240
Volume absorption means the volume will absorb&nbsp;
light as it passes through an object. This is kind&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:24.240 --> 00:23:28.480
of what happens when you’re looking into a pond&nbsp;
and light starts to disappear as it gets deeper.&nbsp;

00:23:29.040 --> 00:23:33.360
Volume scatter is more like what you see&nbsp;
with fog and every scene is better with a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:33.360 --> 00:23:38.480
little fog in it. With volume scatter, light&nbsp;
hits the volume and bounces around. This can&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:38.480 --> 00:23:43.120
be very demanding on a computer to calculate so&nbsp;
if your computer struggles with Blender, volume&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:43.120 --> 00:23:47.840
shading might not work for you at the moment.
There’s also the principled volume shader which&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:47.840 --> 00:23:52.240
combines the two in the most realistic way&nbsp;
possible and it’s probably the one to use&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:52.240 --> 00:23:55.760
most of the time. It also hasn’t been&nbsp;
around forever and before you had to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:55.760 --> 00:24:00.480
mix a scatter and absorption node together&nbsp;
got get what this node can do by itself.&nbsp;

00:24:00.480 --> 00:24:06.240
We plug the volume into the volume channel and&nbsp;
we get this, some pretty dense fog. We can slide&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:06.240 --> 00:24:11.200
the density down to reduce the fog, but notice&nbsp;
it’s a very uniform fog throughout the object.&nbsp;

00:24:11.760 --> 00:24:15.840
Using texture nodes, color ramps and other&nbsp;
things we can tweak this density value to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:15.840 --> 00:24:20.640
get really cool effects. I’ll add a noise texture,&nbsp;
which we didn’t really cover, but it’s similar to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:20.640 --> 00:24:25.840
the musgrave texture node. This one has a factor&nbsp;
output which we can plug into the density input of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:25.840 --> 00:24:31.680
the volume shader. It might be difficult to see,&nbsp;
but as we adjust the scale of this noise texture,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:31.680 --> 00:24:36.240
there are sort of noisy pockets of&nbsp;
fog that we can adjust the size of.&nbsp;

00:24:36.240 --> 00:24:40.400
We could add a color ramp between these&nbsp;
two to adjust the fog similarly to how&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:40.400 --> 00:24:42.240
we adjusted things with the surface material.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:44.560 --> 00:24:50.560
We can change the color of the volume which might&nbsp;
make this easier to see. We can have the fog give&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:50.560 --> 00:24:55.040
off its own light which isn’t really realistic&nbsp;
but it can create a cool effect. There are a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:55.040 --> 00:24:59.520
lot of other things to play around with here too.
And I should point out we see a new color socket&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:59.520 --> 00:25:04.080
here. These blue sockets are for attribute&nbsp;
inputs which is, as of this recording,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:04.080 --> 00:25:08.240
a fairly new feature of Blender that I haven’t&nbsp;
fully wrapped my head around yet. They’re useful&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:08.240 --> 00:25:14.240
in geometry nodes which are an entirely different&nbsp;
use of nodes that this video is not getting into.&nbsp;

00:25:14.240 --> 00:25:18.400
What you could do with this object is to make&nbsp;
the object huge and have it encompass your entire&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:18.400 --> 00:25:23.360
scene to add fog to it, but remember volume is&nbsp;
very demanding when rendering so use with caution&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:23.360 --> 00:25:28.080
and don’t go crazier than you need to with it.
Since we are using a noise texture to control&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:28.080 --> 00:25:34.320
the fog density here, we could change it to 4D&nbsp;
which gives us that W value we discussed before.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:34.320 --> 00:25:38.080
We could use that along with keyframes&nbsp;
to animate the density of the fog.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:38.640 --> 00:25:42.560
Hard to see in preview mode but it could&nbsp;
look something like this when rendered out.

00:25:44.000 --> 00:25:47.600
I promised some helpful tips at&nbsp;
the end of Part 1 so here we go.

00:25:47.600 --> 00:25:52.400
When you find yourself adding the same node to a&nbsp;
lot of materials. Like the color ramp for example,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:52.400 --> 00:25:57.680
you can speed this up two ways. Press Shift+A&nbsp;
to add a material. Find the node you want and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:57.680 --> 00:26:02.800
right-click it. You can either add a shortcut&nbsp;
for the node. By doing this, you’ll be prompted&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:02.800 --> 00:26:07.440
to press a key to create a shortcut. But,&nbsp;
how many keys do you have on your keyboard?&nbsp;

00:26:07.440 --> 00:26:11.760
Some useless trivia - the standard&nbsp;
keyboard actually has 101 keys on it.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:11.760 --> 00:26:15.920
I didn’t count them, I Googled it.
What I prefer is to add nodes to my&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:15.920 --> 00:26:19.920
quick favorites menu. Right click the&nbsp;
node and choose add to quick favorites.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:20.560 --> 00:26:25.520
Now, when in the shader editor, we can press “Q”&nbsp;
and a short menu of your favorite nodes appear.

00:26:26.880 --> 00:26:31.920
With the node wrangler addon enabled you can do&nbsp;
so many things and here are just a few of them.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:31.920 --> 00:26:34.480
Make sure you remember to turn&nbsp;
on the node wrangler addon.

00:26:35.200 --> 00:26:38.320
If you want to disconnect a&nbsp;
node connection, press control&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:38.320 --> 00:26:42.640
and then right click on your mouse. With those&nbsp;
pressed, just cut through the connections you&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:42.640 --> 00:26:46.880
want to disconnect and they’re gone. You can&nbsp;
do this across multiple connections at once.

00:26:47.840 --> 00:26:53.120
In Blender, it’s often useful to see what one&nbsp;
single node in your node tree is contributing.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:53.120 --> 00:26:58.240
You can do this as long as node wrangler is turned&nbsp;
on. Hold down Control Shift on your keyboard and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:58.240 --> 00:27:04.160
then click on a node. It connects that node into&nbsp;
this viewer node and then into the final output.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:04.160 --> 00:27:09.280
So you can Control Shift click around to see&nbsp;
what your nodes all look like by themselves.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:09.280 --> 00:27:13.040
When you’re done, Control Shift Click the&nbsp;
final shader node and it’ll go back to normal.

00:27:14.080 --> 00:27:18.320
When you have a texture node in your editor&nbsp;
and want to connect it to a mapping and texture&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:18.320 --> 00:27:23.440
coordinate node, you can save a lot of time&nbsp;
by selecting the node and pressing Control T.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:23.440 --> 00:27:25.680
It automatically sets up the connection for you.

00:27:27.120 --> 00:27:31.920
Here are a few ways to organize your nodes. You&nbsp;
can drag with your mouse to select several nodes&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:31.920 --> 00:27:38.160
and then press CONTROL + J and it will frame these&nbsp;
nodes. You can click the frame and drag the entire&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:38.160 --> 00:27:42.400
frame around. You can still move nodes around&nbsp;
within the frame and the frame will adjust its&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:42.400 --> 00:27:47.200
size as needed. Press “N” on your keyboard&nbsp;
to open up a sidebar in the shader editor.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:47.200 --> 00:27:50.640
Here you can label the frame, let’s give&nbsp;
it a nice name that you should remember.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:51.440 --> 00:27:56.160
You can check color and give it a color&nbsp;
background. Under properties, you can&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:56.160 --> 00:28:02.160
increase the size of the label up to 64 font.&nbsp;
This is a great way to organize large node trees.

00:28:02.160 --> 00:28:06.720
You can also create node groups. Let’s&nbsp;
say we wanted this node and this node to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:06.720 --> 00:28:12.320
be condensed into one single node. Select them&nbsp;
and press Control+G. Whoa, what just happened?&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:12.320 --> 00:28:18.240
Blender created a node group with a group input,&nbsp;
then the two nodes and then a group output. Press&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:18.240 --> 00:28:23.760
“tab” to go back to our node tree. Here, the two&nbsp;
nodes have been combined into one node group.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:23.760 --> 00:28:27.920
We can again name the group, give it a&nbsp;
color and pressing tab while it’s selected&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:27.920 --> 00:28:32.480
will take us back into the node group.
If we had a value inside the node group&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:32.480 --> 00:28:37.040
that we wanted controlled without having to&nbsp;
tab into the node group, we can connect the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:37.040 --> 00:28:43.520
empty socket on the group input into the value&nbsp;
we want to control. Now tab out, and we see we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:43.520 --> 00:28:48.480
can control that strength value right here from&nbsp;
the group node. Super useful to stay organized.

00:28:49.040 --> 00:28:54.480
In Part 2 of this Blender tutorial, I’m gonna&nbsp;
cover PBR textures which use images to create&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:54.480 --> 00:28:58.800
super realistic materials. I’ll have more&nbsp;
quick tips at the end of Part 2 as well.

00:28:58.800 --> 00:29:01.280
My name is Brandon and I’m&nbsp;
a Blender Artist. Thank you,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:01.280 --> 00:29:05.040
thank you, thank you for all your support&nbsp;
and I’ll see you in Part 2. Stay creative!

